results.notes:
Growing in rocky disturbed drainage ditches bordering pine and oak treeline. Fruiting with many other Inocybe sp, one was growing from the same hole in the dirt as an Inocybe.

Caps quickly fading to tan after removing the leaf litter protecting them, one appeared to be faintly striate but maybe not.

Gills fairly well spaced and sub-decurrent or attached with a slightly decurrent tooth? Sadly I couldnt get them to drop spores but the gills have dried to a brownish color.

Stem fairly sturdy, purplish tinted mycelium at the base.

At first I assumed they were a Deconica because of the slightly decurrent gils and possibly striate hygrophanous cap. After further investigation im leaning towards something in Cortinarius subgenus telamonia, C. flexipes seems real close.

results.notes:
this was found by Patty just as we turned around to head back down the trail. neither of us had any idea what it was. I marveled at it the whole walk back and for rest of the day. the hesitant and provisional consensus was “maybe a slime mold,” but the one FB which was sectioned was just too firm for that theory to hold. once it was determined that the substrate was Gambel oak, some process of elimination on the USDA Fungus Host Database and MycoPortal lead to the name Endothia singularis, a member of the Cryphonectriaceae (which explains the consistency). results.notes:
Fruiting in heavy, nitrogen rich bark mulch-some fruiting bodies in collection attached to deer droppings. Cap: has a less papillate cap center/apex than true P. semilanceata. Smaller in stature than P. semilanceata and or P. pelliculosa. Less yellow and darker brown overall in fresh specimens than P. silvatica.

Caps are hygrophanous and change quickly from viscid brown/tan to white and somewhat buff with dark purple/brown spore deposits to cap margin and gill edges.

Spore print: purple brown.

Not fruiting in grass, but rather in bark mulch.

Stems: White at base, bruising blue when handled, fragile(not flexible as with P. semilanceata).

Harvested a collection of over ten specimens from this collection for microscopy and herbarium storage for future analysis and study.

Odor: farinaceous, the classic powdered sugar scent of most Psilocybin containing species.

Willing to send this for DNA analysis/sequencing if the opportunity arises.
